Main IT - Univariate analysis

Fabio Torreggiani

Created: 2nd November 2023; Updated: 15th December 2023

Purpose: Running descriptive analysis on all the measured variables, divided by mechanism and, when needed, compared with either the reference population.

Summary

  • Representativity of the sample. Representative of gender and more or less of age (slightly younger), but not representative at all in terms of education: much more educated than the general population. Sinistra Ecologia e Libert and Movimento 5 Stelle oversampled.

  • Twitter. Half of the sample has it and uses it regularly, especially for lurking (78% at least once a week; 50% for active use).

  • Cognitive effort. Tasks where quite difficult: 50% of sample got 0 correct, another 25% got just one correct and only around 10% got all correct.

  • Politics. Party affiliation is relatively similar to that of general population, especially accounting for the coding mistake on Forza Italia. Left-Right orientation present a quasi-normal distribution, with anchoring on the extremes and at the center.

  • Institutions. Pretty low trust, with all institutions with mean below middle point of the scale, except for Universities. Social media have the lowest trust (mean 0.3/1). Government the one with highest SD (polarized as expected), but not radically different from others. In general, Press, Parliament and Government have the more similar distributions. Trust in science is pretty high according to both measures. Other considerations in PCA report.

  • Anti-elitism. Distributions are squeezed over the top of the scale in all cases: most people chose extremely high answers. The least concentrated distributions is that of third item (politicians listen to people), which also have some answers in the middle and low part of he scale. This item is also the one that is more strongly (negatively) correlated with trust in political institutions. The opposite is true for second item (difference between people and elite).

  • Social Norms - Beliefs. Not a clear preference for accuracy, but a bi-modal distribution: accuracy and interest are at the exact same level. This is not the case for personal normative beliefs, where there is a clear preference for accuracy (while interest mantain the second place not far behind). This is an indication that participants understood the questions and that there is a fraction of people recognizing that they value interest when they should value accuracy.

  • Social Norms - Expectations. People are quite good at guessing the unclear/mixed situation regarding the norm. The mode answer is more or less half of the sample, followed by around a quarter. This result is true for both empirical and normative expectations and it is the same as in the Italian convenience sample. Also, there is a link between beliefs and expectations, but not a very strong one: the incidence of accuracy is higher in almost everyone.

  • Media Consumption. The most consumed media are internet, phones and tv news, which are consumed more ore less by everyone and on a very frequent base. Other media are more niche, in the sense that they have both people using them a lot and others using them never or very rarely: newspaper, radionews, social media and emails. Friends are consumed by more or less everyone, but with varying frequency.

  • Perceived Accuracy. Sort of bi-modal, but not coinciding with the two extremes: extremely accurate is the least chosen category. In general, people were both skeptical (generally low scores, even for reliable news) and good at discerning news (still, there is a gap between fake and reliable news).

  • Perceived Accuracy - Events. Differently to what noted in other studies, people were good at discerning news, independently of the event analysed. For 17 out of 20 events the reliable news is significantly perceived as more accurate than the fake news. Then, there are two events for which the scores are not statistically distinguishable between the true and fake news. Finally, there is an event (event 20, like in the other 2 studies) for which the perc. acc. is higher for the fake than the reliable news. This result could also be simply due to the higher numerosity of the sample.

  • Perceived Accuracy - Round and Treatment. No effect of round: people are not better (nor worse) as the survey proceed. No effect of treatment: truth discernment is not better or worse after the treatment, in none of the groups.

  • Robustness Checks - Individual Perceived Accuracy. In general, the distribution is very close to a normal one. Divided by veracity, the curve for fake news is squeezed toward the bottom of the scale and seems cut: a lot of people choose the bottom of the scale for fake news. Individual truth discernment present a normal distribution with high kurtosis and a relatively weak right skewness.

  • Robustness Checks - Balance of news. The balance of news (% of fake news over the ten items) is a normal distribution (randomization worked correctly). There is no effect of balance on truth discernment: people judged items one by one, without inferring the balance of true vs fake news and trying to guess the accuracy based on that.

  • Sharing behavior. As expected, it is a very rare behaviour and linked with perceived accuracy (correlation of 0.64).

# General population data
genpop_df_AGe <- read.csv("C:/Users/fabio/Documents/Universita/Dottorato/Survey anti-el socnorm/data analysis/general population data/Italy/age_gender_IT.csv")
names(genpop_df_AGe) <- c("DEM_AGE", "Uomo", "Donna", "Total")

min_age = summary(part_df$DEM_AGE)[[1]]
max_age = summary(part_df$DEM_AGE)[[6]]
# Building dataset for plot
temp_df <- part_df$DEM_AGECat %>% table() %>% prop.table() %>% as.data.frame()
names(temp_df) <- c("DEM_AGECat", "Frequency")

temp_df2 <- genpop_df_AGe %>%
  # filtering non-numerical rows
  filter(!DEM_AGE %in% c("Totale", "100 e oltre"),
         # filtering by same ages of sample
                         as.numeric(DEM_AGE) >= min_age &
                           as.numeric(DEM_AGE) <= max_age) %>%
  # collapsing into age categories
  mutate(DEM_AGECat = ifelse(DEM_AGE >= min_age & DEM_AGE < 25, "18-24",
                         ifelse(DEM_AGE >= 25 & DEM_AGE < 35, "25-34",
                                ifelse(DEM_AGE >= 35 & DEM_AGE < 45, "35-44",
                                       ifelse(DEM_AGE >= 45 & DEM_AGE < 55, "45-54", "55plus"))))) %>% 
  # creating total and frequency by age group
  group_by(DEM_AGECat) %>% summarise(Total = sum(Total)) %>% mutate(TotPop = sum(Total), GenPop = Total/TotPop)
# Visualization
temp_df %>% inner_join(select(temp_df2, DEM_AGECat, GenPop)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = DEM_AGECat, y = Frequency)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_col(aes(y = GenPop), alpha = 0.25, linetype = "dashed", fill = NA, color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Age Categories", caption = "Distribution of the general population represented with dashed lines. \nSource: ISTAT 2023")

# Building dataset for plot
temp_df <- table(part_df$DEM_GENDER) %>% as.data.frame() %>% filter(Var1 %in% c("Uomo", "Donna"))
names(temp_df) <- c("DEM_GENDER", "GroupSum")

temp_df2 <- genpop_df_AGe %>%
  # filtering by same ages of sample
  filter(as.numeric(DEM_AGE) >= min_age &
           as.numeric(DEM_AGE) <= max_age) %>%
  pivot_longer(col = 2:3,
               names_to = "DEM_GENDER") %>%
  group_by(DEM_GENDER) %>% summarise(
    GroupSum = sum(value)
  ) %>% mutate(Tot = sum(GroupSum), GenPop = GroupSum/Tot)
# Visualization
temp_df %>% mutate(Tot = sum(GroupSum), Frequency = GroupSum/Tot) %>%
  inner_join(select(temp_df2, DEM_GENDER, GenPop), by = "DEM_GENDER") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = DEM_GENDER, y = Frequency)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_col(aes(y = GenPop), alpha = 0.25, linetype = "dashed", fill = NA, color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Gender", caption = "Distribution of the general population represented with dashed lines. \nSource: ISTAT 2023")

names(genpop_df_Edu) <- c("DEM_EDUCat", "GroupTot")
# Building dataset for plot
temp_df <- part_df$DEM_EDU4Cat %>% as_factor() %>% fct_collapse(
  MiddleOrLower = c("MiddleSchool"),
  BachOrHigher = c("Bachelor", "Master")
) %>% table() %>% as.data.frame()
names(temp_df) <- c("DEM_EDUCat", "GroupSum")

  MiddleOrLower = c("licenza di scuola elementare, nessun titolo di studio", "licenza di scuola media"),
  HighSchool = c("diploma"),
  BachOrHigher = c("laurea e post-laurea")
)

Redistribution

myBarPlot <- function(var_n){
  ggplot(aes(x = .data[[var_n]]), data = part_df) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..))) +
  guides(x = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2)) +
  labs(x = var_n, y = "frequency") +
  scale_x_discrete(label = function(x) stringr::str_trunc(x, 30)) +
  coord_flip()
}

mySummary <- function(var_n){
  a <- sprintf("Summary of: %s", var_n)
  b <- part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]] %>% summary()
  c <- sprintf("Mean: %.2f", mean(part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]], na.rm = T))
  d <- sprintf("Sd: %.2f", sd(part_df[[paste0(var_n, "Num")]], na.rm = T))
  cat(a, "\n")
  print(b)
  cat(c, d)
}

  summarise(n = n(),
            avg = round(t.test(ACCNum)$estimate, 3),
            lci = t.test(ACCNum)$conf.int[1],
            uci = t.test(ACCNum)$conf.int[2]) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = veracity, y = avg)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(x = veracity, ymin = lci, ymax = uci, width = 0.4)) +
  ylim(0, 5)

Avg. Perc. per Event

sum_event <- answ_df %>% group_by(event) %>%
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    avg_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$estimate,
    lci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate,
    lci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[1] -
      t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[2],
    lci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    p_val = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$p.value,
    sign_Diff = ifelse(p_val < 0.05, 1, 0),
    highest = max(avg_Fake, avg_Rel)
  )
sum_event %>% pivot_longer(cols = -c(event, n, avg_Diff, lci_Diff, uci_Diff, p_val, sign_Diff, highest),
               names_to = c(".value", "veracity"),
               names_sep = "_",
               values_drop_na = T) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(event, avg_Diff), y = avg, fill = veracity)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(x = "Events",
       y = "Perceived accuracy",
       caption = paste0("Stars indicate that, for a specific event, 
       \nthe avg. perc. acc. is significanlty different between the fake and rel. post.
                        \n\nEvents for which diff. is not sign. at 95% level: ",
                         paste(as.character(sum_event$event[sum_event$sign_Diff == 0]), collapse = " "))) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ifelse(sign_Diff, "*", ""), y = highest, group = event), 
            vjust = -.1, hjust = .5, size = 20 / .pt) +
  ylim(0,4) +
  theme(plot.caption = element_text(lineheight = .5))

               values_drop_na = T) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = round, y = avg, fill = veracity)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(x = "Round",
       y = "Perceived accuracy",
       caption = paste0("Stars indicate that, for a specific event, 
       \nthe avg. perc. acc. is significanlty different between the fake and rel. post.
                        \n\nEvents for which diff. is not sign. at 95% level: ",
                         paste(as.character(sum_event$event[sum_event$sign_Diff == 0]), collapse = " "))) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ifelse(sign_Diff, "*", ""), y = highest, group = round), 
            vjust = -.1, hjust = .5, size = 20 / .pt) +
  ylim(0,4) +
  theme(plot.caption = element_text(lineheight = .5))

Truth disc. per round and treat.

sum_event <- answ_df %>% group_by(round, treat_group) %>%
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    avg_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$estimate,
    lci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Fake = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate,
    lci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Rel = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    avg_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[1] -
      t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$estimate[2],
    lci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[1],
    uci_Diff = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$conf.int[2],
    p_val = t.test(ACCNum[veracity == "Fake"], 
                      ACCNum[veracity == "Reliable"])$p.value,
    sign_Diff = ifelse(p_val < 0.05, 1, 0),
    highest = max(avg_Fake, avg_Rel)
  )
